The Two-Pointers Technique is a simple yet powerful strategy where you use two indices (pointers) that traverse a data structure -
such as an array, list, or string - either toward each other or in the same direction to solve problems more efficiently.

When to Use Two Pointers:
Sorted Input : If the array or list is already sorted (or can be sorted), two pointers can efficiently find pairs or ranges.
Pairs or SubArrays : When the problem asks about two elements, sub-arrays, or ranges instead of working with single elements.
Sliding Window Problems : When you need to maintain a window of elements that grows/shrinks based on conditions.
Linked Lists (Slow–Fast pointers) : Detecting cycles, finding the middle node, or checking palindrome property.

Advantages:
Time Efficiency : Many problems that would require O(n^2) time with nested loops can be solved in O(n) time using two pointers.

In nested loops, or every new i, j starts again from near the beginning , so the pointers are starting from the beginning (so O(n2)).
In two pointers, we are not starting from the beginning every time, we are starting from where we left off, so we are not doing the same work again and again.